{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01H1HsPkhfCDLCkrZQSNqBqw","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The Prometheus API shows that it's running with the OLD configuration, without the rabbitmq job. But the pod's config file (`cat /etc/prometheus/prometheus.yml`) shows the new config with the rabbitmq job.\n\nThis is interesting. The config file in the pod IS updated (the ConfigMap was updated and the file is mounted properly), but Prometheus's loaded configuration is still the old one. The reload notification said it loaded the config, but the actual loaded config still shows the old one.\n\nWait, let me check the Prometheus logs more carefully. The log shows:\n1. Started at `10:12:21` with the old config (only prometheus scrape job)\n2. Reloaded at `10:13:15`, but the API still shows the old configuration\n\nThis doesn't add up—the reload signal was supposedly successful, yet the loaded config hasn't changed. Let me reconsider the timeline: the pod started at 10:12:21, and the ConfigMap was patched after that, so the pod was already running when the update happened. I need to figure out exactly when I sent the reload signal and whether it actually took effect.\n\nThe real issue might be timing. Kubernetes can take up to 60 seconds to update mounted ConfigMap files, so when I triggered the reload immediately after patching, the file on disk might not have been updated yet. The reload at 10:13:15 could have happened before the file was actually written to the pod's filesystem. Let me trigger another reload now that I know the file has definitely been updated.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":628,"cache_read_input_tokens":37602,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":628},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":